<div class="comment-wrapper"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment"><div class="avatar"><img src="https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d745cdc85e6df10fd8691b06ff840e5f?s=50"></div><header><strong>SE-0025: Scoped Access Level, next steps</strong> from <string>Michael M. Mayer</string> &lt;m.mayer6 at gmail.com&gt;<p>April  6, 2016 at 10:00:00pm</p></header><div class="content"><p>I am opposed to any change to the current access level system.  <br>What we have now is simple, approachable and handles all real cases <br>for limiting or granting access.  Any additions will just serve to <br>complicate the current system without sufficient offsetting benefit.  <br>Further additions will just handle cases for which there are already <br>other viable solutions.<br></p><p>Furthermore, any additions to the access level system would be contrary <br>to the stated goal of streamlining the Swift language.<br></p><p>Thank you for the opportunity to contribute to the discussion.<br></p><p>Regards, Michael<br>m.mayer6 at gmail.com<br></p></div></li></ul></div>    </main>
